#. §0: `induction <x> generalizing <y> with ..`
#. §1: `induction`
#. §2: `f(x, y, z) = g(x)`
#. §3: `x`
#. §4: `f(x, y, z) = g(x)`
#. §5: `f(x + 1, y, z) = g(x + 1)`
#. §6: `f(x + 1, 2 * y, √ z) = g(x + 1)`
#. §7: `f(x, y, z) = g(x)`
#. §8: `y`
#. §9: `z`
#. §10: `induction x with`
#. §11: `induction x generalizing y z with`
#. §12: `∀ (y z), f(x, y, z) = g(x)`
#. §13: `f(x, y, z) = g(x)`
#. §14: `rw [induction_hyp (2 * y) (√ z)]`
#. §15: `y`
#. §16: `z`
#. §17: `rw`
#: Game.Levels.AlgebraWorld.L05_Vandermonde
msgid "Vandermonde's Identity is a fundamental combinatorial formula expressing that the sum of products of\n"
"binomial coefficients equals a single binomial coefficient. For non-negative integers m, n, and r\n"
"where r ≤ m + n, the identity is\n"
"∑ (k = 0 till k = r) (choose m k) * (choose n (r - k)) = choose (m + n) r\n"
"\n"
"# induction generalizing\n"
"To prove it, you will need a new tool in your belt: §0\n"
"It's an extension of the §1 tactic that allows you to induct better on functions with multiple\n"
"arguments.\n"
"\n"
"Say you need to prove §2 by induction on §3. Your induction hypothesis will eventually\n"
"become §4 and goal state §5.  However, what if, in the process of\n"
"manipulating/rewriting the function, you get a goal state of say §6?\n"
"You can no longer substitute the induction hypothesis §7 because the variables §8 and §9\n"
"are different.\n"
"\n"
"Fear not!  You just need to change the first line from §10 to\n"
"§11.  This changes your induction hypothesis to\n"
"§12 instead of just §13.  Now, you can still substitute this\n"
"hypothesis into your goal state by doing §14 (or whatever your induction\n"
"hypothesis is named and whatever y and z you want).\n"
"\n"
"Remember, you have to give §15 and §16 as arguments in this case before you can use §17 on it!"
msgstr ""

